folder: Greenwich Street & Morris Street, Manhattan, NY
text:
Greenwich Street(left), south from a point midway between Morris Street and Battery Place, and to the latter, showing the lower half of the block square site that is to be razed for the proposed Brooklyn-Battery Tunnel.

Washington Street is on the right, where appears the lower portions of the Whitehall Building. At the top is the Park. The buildings in the foreground are No's. 22-24 Greenwich Street and No. 23 Washington Street. They are back to back and adjoin the parking lot shown.

The point of vantage for the photographer is the Cunard Building on the opposite side of Greenwich Street. The "El" tracks are on same.

Staff Photographer
New York Post

March, 1940

folder: Greenwich Street & Trinity Place, Manhattan, NY
text:
The convergence of Greenwich Street (left) and Trinity Place (right), at Morris Street. Shown at that point is the triangular structure that separates the first two mentioned thoroughfares. This building bears No. 28 Greenwich Street. Note the fact that the Sixth Avenue Elevated that formerly ran on Trinity Place has been removed. The Ninth Avenue Line that still remains on Greenwich Street is to be demolished sometime in 1940-1.
At the left margin is a portion of the 35 story No. 19 Rector Street Building. Thru the center is the Electric Bond & Share Building. On the right, and separated by Trinity Churchyard are the Trinity and the Empire Buildings.

April 28, 1940

P. L. Sperr

Greenwich Street and Trinity Place, at point of intersection.

P. L. Sperr

P.L. Sperr, photographer
